        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and he became",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " one of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the priests of the high places",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The insertion of the italic ‘one of’ shews that the construction is irregular. The R.V. gives, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "that there might be priests of the high places",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". But the awkwardness of the Hebrew which has the verb in the singular and the noun in the plural is not removed thereby. It can be explained but not imitated in a translation. ‘Whosoever would’ in the previous clause is singular in form but plural in notion. Hence the latter portion of the verse says ‘whosoever would he became,’ but as there were many who did so, the result was not one priest but many ‘priests of the high places.’",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
